# 🐍 Python FastAPI Backend Rules

## 🔧 Core Principles
- Follow PEP8 strictly (formatting, naming, spacing).
- Use Python 3.12+ features where appropriate.
- Prefer readability over cleverness.
- Follow DRY and SOLID principles.
- Use type hints everywhere (no untyped functions).

## 📁 Project Structure
- Use modular architecture:
  - app/
    - api/
    - services/
    - repositories/
    - models/
    - schemas/
    - core/
    - utils/
- Separate concerns strictly:
  - API → request/response
  - service → business logic
  - repository → DB access

## ⚙️ FastAPI Standards
- Use dependency injection (`Depends`) for services.
- Always use Pydantic models for request/response validation.
- Never expose raw ORM models in API responses.
- Use async/await for all I/O operations.

## 🧾 Naming Conventions
- snake_case for variables/functions
- PascalCase for classes
- UPPER_CASE for constants
- Boolean variables must start with: is_, has_, can_

## 🚨 Error Handling
- Use centralized exception handling (custom exceptions).
- Never expose internal errors to clients.
- Validate inputs at API boundary.
- Use early returns for validation errors.

## 🔐 Security
- Always validate user input.
- Use JWT/OAuth2 for authentication.
- Never hardcode secrets (use env variables).
- Hash passwords with bcrypt or argon2.
- Use HTTPS for all external calls.

## 🗄️ Database
- Use SQLAlchemy (async) or Prisma client.
- Use repository pattern for DB operations.
- Avoid raw queries unless necessary.
- Always handle transactions properly.

## 🧪 Testing
- Use pytest.
- Write unit tests for services.
- Mock external dependencies.
- Minimum 80% coverage.

## 📊 Logging & Monitoring
- Use structured logging (loguru or standard logging).
- Log errors with context.
- Never log sensitive data.

## ⚡ Performance
- Use async APIs.
- Avoid blocking calls.
- Cache frequently accessed data (Redis).

## 🧹 Code Style
- Max function length: 30 lines.
- Max file length: 300 lines.
- Use early returns instead of nested conditions.
- Avoid deep nesting (>3 levels).

## 📦 API Design
- RESTful conventions:
  - GET /users
  - POST /users
  - GET /users/{id}
- Use versioning: /api/v1/
- Always return consistent response format:
  {
    "success": true,
    "data": {},
    "error": null
  }

## 🧠 AI Behavior Rules
- Do not generate placeholder logic.
- If unsure, add TODO with explanation.
- Prefer complete working code over partial snippets.
